<div id="review_766248822" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/766248822" />
    <a title="Jill" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1013193-jill"><img alt="Jill" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1391401243p2/1013193.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/766248822?book_show_action=true">Nov 15, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jill" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jill" href="/user/show/1013193-jill">Jill</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1013193-jill?shelf=glbtq">glbtq</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1013193-jill?shelf=nonfiction">nonfiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer766248822" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7721478038683639868">This book is part memoir, part investigative journalism, part ethnographic study, and entirely amazing. I felt like I learned so much about the trans culture (or at least this one small part of it), though when I began I didn&apos;t consider myself uneducated. I guess I was! Or at least, I hadn&apos;t thought about it as deeply as Beam asked me to go. And I went there. Oh, I went there. And it was worth it.<br/><br/>If you liked this book, or like her writing style but not this topic, her book <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/16691891.To_the_End_of_June_The_Intimate_Life_of_American_Foster_Care' title='To the End of June The Intimate Life of American Foster Care by Cris Beam' rel='nofollow noopener'>To the End of June: T</a></span>
  <span id="freeText7721478038683639868" style="display:none">This book is part memoir, part investigative journalism, part ethnographic study, and entirely amazing. I felt like I learned so much about the trans culture (or at least this one small part of it), though when I began I didn't consider myself uneducated. I guess I was! Or at least, I hadn't thought about it as deeply as Beam asked me to go. And I went there. Oh, I went there. And it was worth it.<br /><br />If you liked this book, or like her writing style but not this topic, her book <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/16691891.To_the_End_of_June_The_Intimate_Life_of_American_Foster_Care" title="To the End of June The Intimate Life of American Foster Care by Cris Beam" rel="nofollow noopener">To the End of June: The Intimate Life of American Foster Care</a> is equally good. I wish she had an update on the lives of those she writes about in this book, because I want to know how they are doing now. I can't believe it's been so long since she wrote it, because it still seemed relevant.</span>
  <a data-text-id="7721478038683639868" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


