<div id="review_8440827" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/8440827" />
    <a title="Meg" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/585005-meg"><img alt="Meg" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1193686285p2/585005.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/8440827?book_show_action=true">Oct 30, 2007</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Meg" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Meg" href="/user/show/585005-meg">Meg</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer8440827" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14861017499372408477">this was a really eye-opening book for me. written compassionately with a tone of healthy curiosity, cris beam provides thorough explanation of trans-life, processes, identities, struggles, and labels within the stories of the youth she works with. i was really impressed with this book, and even more surprised that harcourt published it. a must-read for the general public, especially those who are ignorant to gender/identity theory and the &quot;alternative&quot; lifestyles of the lgtb community.</span>
  <span id="freeText14861017499372408477" style="display:none">this was a really eye-opening book for me. written compassionately with a tone of healthy curiosity, cris beam provides thorough explanation of trans-life, processes, identities, struggles, and labels within the stories of the youth she works with. i was really impressed with this book, and even more surprised that harcourt published it. a must-read for the general public, especially those who are ignorant to gender/identity theory and the "alternative" lifestyles of the lgtb community.</span>
  <a data-text-id="14861017499372408477" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

